		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">If there is a bunch of people which we want to tell apart, of course, we call their names. But what to do if we don't know them? What if there are too many?  Or the same name twice? There might be people we cannot recognize (change of hair colour, don't see their face...) Look at the two trefoil knots (p. B). No matter how we twist or deform we cannot make them look the same without cutting. They are DIFFERENT! The figure eight knot (p. B) is used by climbers: it's a question of life or death to make sure that pulling does not loosen.Hence, the task is to find an invariant which tells knots apart but also knows when a knot loosens... and this for infinitely many knots!In the 1920's Alexander associated a polynomial to each knot - the same when knots differ by twisting and deforming. But he couldn't distinguish the two trefoil knots. In 1984 Jones found a better recipe: the Jones polynomial could distinguish the trefoils, but still cannot tell apart many other knots. This has to be improved! We also want to consider cobordisms, surfaces which have knots as boundaries (e.g. the pair of pants going between two and one trivial knot, p. C), and get an invariant for these cobordisms -  going between  the invariants associated to the boundary knots. Problem: these surfaces can become rather complicated!Very recently, I managed to find such an invariant and I believe it's a very good one! It can distinguish more than the Jones polynomial and also  sees  the cobordisms. Here is the idea: Assume we have a polynomial, say 2+x. Imagine this says in which floors people live: two parties in the ground floor and one in the first (just as the crossings in the trefoil knots). So far we don't know if the house is on the left or right hand side of the street (just as the left trefoil is a mirror image of the right one). We have to include the house number, the street etc - a big amount of data! We have to  categorify  them while keeping track of ALL their relations (the cobordisms) ...The mathematical tool is category theory: it describes in a very abstract, precise and complete way the relationship between many objects (e.g. why the first floor is  naturally  below the second ). The problem of categorifying appears everywhere. The challenge is to find a good categorification, easy, but with all information. And then it should be conceptual or computable (or both). For the knot problem I found a good categorification, but a nice description is still missing. I want to have* a diagrammatical description - adapted to computers* a geometric description - conceptual, but built on deep mathematical techniques, ideally in terms of a single object, which should carry extra structure (like symmetries).The next objective is to find invariants for ALL surfaces, not just for ones  which go between knots . Any solution has immense impact in mathematics, but also in the way theoretical physics describes the world developing in time. Knot invariants are also useful to understand DNA packing ([S]). I bring with me the experience of thinking in abstract and complicated structures and have the representation theoretic tools for good categorifications.  The challenge (and fascination!) of the project is the interplay of different areas of mathematics. In my previous work I could show that I am capable to master this task.To carry out the programme I need help from specialists. I will continue to communicate with people in Glasgow and to visit universities worldwide to discuss new developments. This month I am in US (at Yale) to visit Frenkel, an expert in mathematical physics. I give talks in Yale and also at the MIT in Boston. In December I will speak at a conference on geometric representation theory in Israel. Through a combination of existing collaborations, my own expertise, hard work and a positive ingenuity I plan to turn this project into a new area of connections, representation theory-topology-geometry</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
